If you have **sudo access** and your instructor allows resetting Jenkins on the exam machine, here are the methods.

## Method 1 (Recommended): Reinstall Jenkins

Stop Jenkins:

```bash
sudo systemctl stop jenkins
```

Remove Jenkins:

```bash
sudo apt purge -y jenkins
sudo apt autoremove -y
```

Delete Jenkins data:

```bash
sudo rm -rf /var/lib/jenkins
sudo rm -rf /etc/default/jenkins
sudo rm -rf /var/log/jenkins
```

Reinstall:

```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y jenkins
```

Start Jenkins:

```bash
sudo systemctl start jenkins
sudo systemctl enable jenkins
```

Get the initial admin password:

```bash
sudo cat /var/lib/jenkins/secrets/initialAdminPassword
```

Open:

```
http://localhost:8080
```

Paste the password and create a new admin user.

---

## Method 2: Disable Security (Only if permitted)

Edit the Jenkins config:

```bash
sudo nano /var/lib/jenkins/config.xml
```

Change:

```xml
<useSecurity>true</useSecurity>
```

to

```xml
<useSecurity>false</useSecurity>
```

Restart Jenkins:

```bash
sudo systemctl restart jenkins
```

Now Jenkins should open without a login. (After the exam, security should be re-enabled.)

---

## Method 3: Reset the Admin Password

If you only need to change the admin password, you can use the Jenkins Script Console—but that requires logging in first. If you can't log in, reinstalling is generally simpler.

### For your exam

Before reinstalling, check whether Jenkins is already installed and running:

```bash
systemctl status jenkins
```

If it's installed but inaccessible because of unknown credentials, ask the instructor whether they expect you to reuse the existing installation or whether you're allowed to reinstall it. Reinstalling on a shared machine could affect other students if the machine is intended to be reused.
